  footnotes: []
english:
  title: On Beholding Snow and Ice Lingering at the Wall's Base, Reflecting on My Feelings
  author: Hong Gwi-dal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the second month, snow still clings to the wall's shadow,
    While all the forest stirs with springtime's awakening.
    Heaven should have hastened its decree,
    Yet earth itself prolongs the season's delay.

    Upon my pillow, tears fall in thought of my parents,
    Against my window, I inscribe laments for my children.
    So troubling, the affairs of this transient world—
    My temples have already silvered with age.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The wall''s lingering snow serves as a mirror for the speaker''s emotional state: though spring arrives for nature, grief and sorrow linger in the domestic sphere.'
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between Heaven's will and Earth's resistance reflects the speaker's own struggle between acceptance and melancholy.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of tears and inscribed laments emphasizes the poet's preoccupation with family bonds—both ancestral and filial—as the seasons turn.
